PALINDROME BY SPLITTING

You are given an array A of length N.

You can perform the following operation:

Choose an index i such that A[i] > 1
Choose two integers X and Y such that X + Y = A[i] and X ≥ 1 and Y ≥ 1
Replace A[i] with X and Y

After this operation, the length of the array increases by 1.

Your task is to make the array palindromic using the minimum number of operations.

An array is called a palindrome if it reads the same from left to right and right to left.

INPUT FORMAT

The first line contains an integer T
T is the number of test cases

For each test case:
The first line contains an integer N
The second line contains N space-separated integers A1, A2, ..., AN

OUTPUT FORMAT

For each test case, print a single integer — the minimum number of operations required

CONSTRAINTS

1 ≤ T ≤ 100000
1 ≤ N ≤ 100000
1 ≤ Ai ≤ 100000
The sum of N over all test cases does not exceed 200000

SAMPLE INPUT

3
4
3 7 6 4
5
1 4 5 4 1
5
1 2 3 4 5

SAMPLE OUTPUT

2
0
4

EXPLANATION

Test case 1
Array: 3 7 6 4

Split 7 into 1 and 6 → array becomes 3 1 6 6 4
Split 4 into 1 and 3 → array becomes 3 1 6 6 1 3

Now the array becomes palindromic

Test case 2
Array is already a palindrome → 0 operations

Test case 3
Multiple splits are required to make the array symmetric
Minimum operations = 4

===================================
import java.util.*;
public class Main{
    public static void main (String[] args) {
        Scanner sc=new Scanner(System.in);
        int t=sc.nextInt();
        while(t-->0){
            int n=sc.nextInt();
            Deque<Integer> dq=new ArrayDeque<>();
            for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
                dq.addLast(sc.nextInt());
            } 
            int op=0;
            while(dq.size()>1) {
               int l=dq.pollFirst();
               int r=dq.pollLast();
                if(l==r){
                    continue;
                }else if(l<r){
                    dq.addLast(r-l);
                    op++;
                }else {
                    dq.addFirst(l-r);
                    op++;
                } } System.out.println(op);
        }
        
    }
}








